post_text:
On August 26th and 27th Edgeworth and Osborne Elementary Schools will be hosting Kindergarten Orientation for all incoming kindergarten students. Whether participating in the on-campus or online option, all incoming kindergarten students are invited to visit their assigned school building for a small group tour (3-4 people) led by a kindergarten teacher. During the visit, students will have an opportunity to see the school building and spend time exploring a kindergarten classroom.
Families are asked to pre-register between now and August 25. Face coverings are mandatory for the building visit.
We are looking forward to seeing you soon!

https://www.myconferencetime.com/edgeworth/

post_text: Our friends at the Sewickley Valley YMCA are hosting a school supply drive. If you can help, or if you'd like some assistance purchasing supplies, check out to the YMCA's Facebook page.
shared_text:
Sewickley Valley YMCA
July 31 at 3:11 PM ·

Back to school may not feel normal this year. Household budgets are tighter, and the plan to return to school looks different, but the need to return to learning with the necessary school supplies remains the same.

Help give children hope and a great start to school by purchasing school supplies through our Amazon Wish List at https://bit.ly/SchoolSupplyYMCA or drop off school supplies at the Sewickley Valley YMCA before August 14. Don't forget, share this post with friends and family to make an even bigger impact!

1) All parents/guardians of students in grades K-12 (for the 2020-2021 school year) should have received a return-to-school survey. This survey should be completed by Monday, July 27, 2020.

2) QVHS Class of 2020 Graduates and their parents/guardians should have received an email about the upcoming July 31 Graduation event. Please select your time slot by Monday, July 27, 2020.

Didn't get the email? Send us a note at communications@qvsd.org.

Congratulations to six faculty and staff honorees who were recognized for their exceptional work this school year by FRIENDS of Quaker Valley Schools.
Each year, FRIENDS honors those who have gone above and beyond to help children in Quaker Valley School District. Each winner received a cash prize. In lieu of a traditional banquet, this year's event was held virtually.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5tWkRilnaME&feature=youtu.be

Congratulations to the following winners who were nominated by their supervisor and the District's Administration:
Marc Duchin, Quaker Valley High School English Teacher
Lara Grogran, Osborne Elementary School 5th Grade Teacher
Ryan Kelly, Quaker Valley Middle School History Teacher
Kelly Miller, Edgeworth Elementary School Kindergarten Teacher
Alanna Oros, Quaker Valley Middle School Administrative Assistant
Cheryl Smith, Osborne Elementary School Head Custodian

Quaker Valley School District values all differences in our community. The District does not condone discrimination in any way, shape, or form.

It was brought to our attention that an Instagram account is using the name Quaker Valley to promulgate hate speech. The only school district Instagram account used by Quaker Valley School District is quaker_valley.

Instagram allows users to report accounts for inappropriate content, we encourage you to do so, as we immediately did the same.

We are beginning the process of material collection and distribution. Please see below for specific guidelines.

Elementary Material Collection & Distribution will take place during the week of June 8th – June 12th by appointment only. Families should make appointments using the My Conference Time Application. Appointments are approximately 15-minutes in length.

Quaker Valley Middle School material collection and distribution will take place the week of June 8.

Due to the need to share staff, high school collection will not take place until the week of June 15. More information will be published soon.

Quaker Valley School District is reopening the school tracks for walking and jogging to comply with Allegheny County moving to the yellow phase of reopening.
Playgrounds, fields, and courts will remain closed until the green phase of reopening.

We hope you will join us on Friday, May 15, starting at 3 p.m. as Quaker Valley teachers and staff drive by to say hi! More than 100 teachers signed up for the event, covering four routes.

Route 1- Through Leetsdale, the Leetsdale Industrial Park, up Campmeeting Road, and through various neighborhoods along that road (Quaker Village, Bell Acres, etc.)

Route 2- Through Sewickley and into Sewickley Heights

Route 3 - Through Edgeworth and up Little Sewickley Creek Road toward the northern part of Sewickley Hills

Route 4 - Through Osborne, Aleppo, Glenfield, and southern Sewickley Hills.

*Detailed route information will be released before Friday. Visit www.qvsd.org for the latest.

post_text:
Some parts of the District are without power after last night's storms. If your home is without power, please follow the guidelines below (for attendance and assignment submission) for Wednesday, April 8, 2020.

Grades 6-12: If you are unable to log into the app to report attendance before 8 p.m. you may report attendance for Wednesday, April 8, 2020, as soon as power is restored. It will be accepted as excused.

Grades K-5: Please complete the attendance assignment for Wednesday, April 8, 2020 in Schoology (it will remain posted) as soon as power is restored and it will be accepted as excused.

If assignments cannot be submitted due to a power outage, please submit assignments when power is restored and inform your teachers that assignments are late due to loss of power. Full credit will be awarded.

post_text:
Congratulations to QVMS Assistant Principal Dr. Lauren McGuirk, who successfully defended her dissertation on Tuesday, March 31. Her dissertation topic included federal and state regulations relating to educating students with disabilities. Her research examined meeting the needs of students with disabilities in general education classes through co-teaching models. She earns her doctorate in Education Leadership from the University of Pittsburgh. Dr. McGuirk also earned her Superintendent Letter of Eligibility.
Congratulations!
text:
Congratulations to QVMS Assistant Principal Dr. Lauren McGuirk, who successfully defended her dissertation on Tuesday, March 31. Her dissertation topic included federal and state regulations relating to educating students with disabilities. Her research examined meeting the needs of students with disabilities in general education classes through co-teaching models. She earns her doctorate in Education Leadership from the University of Pittsburgh. Dr. McGuirk also earned her Superintendent Letter of Eligibility.
Congratulations!

post_text:
Shortly after 9:00 a.m. this morning, Tuesday, January 28th, staff members reported an odor near the Nurse’s Office at QVMS. The fire department and gas company were immediately notified, and out of an abundance of caution students and staff were safely relocated to St. Andrew’s Church in Sewickley.
At this time, the smell in the building is no longer present and was deemed non-hazardous to the health and safety of our students and staff. The building has been cleared for students to return to school. The District is working with maintenance staff to identify the source of the odor, which is not linked to the presence of gas in the building.

post_text: This morning Quaker Valley Middle School was evacuated due to an odor being reported by staff. The fire department and the gas company have been notified and are investigating. Out of an abundance of caution, all students and staff were relocated to St. Andrew's Church in Sewickley. Everyone is safe and accounted for. We are asking that parents please do not come pick up children at this time. We will provide more information as soon as it's available.

The following Edgeworth Elementary fifth grade students participated in the 2019 Citizenship Challenge Finals, held Tuesday at the Sen. John Heinz History Center in Pittsburgh.

Max Brackney
Giada Buzzelli
Josephine Courtney
Alex Polce
James Rutherford
Tiya Singh
Kate Steinfurth
Maggie Watson

Supported by The Rendell Center for Civics and Civic Engagement, The Citizenship Challenge encouraged 4th and 5th grade students in the Pittsburgh area to express themselves regarding a current issue facing our democracy. Team Edgeworth contributed thoughts and ideas to the following question: The Founding Fathers are considered to be brilliant in relation to the government they created. Which part of the Bill of Rights do you think is the most important and continues to exert the greatest impact on Americans today?

Read more here: https://www.qvsd.org/apps/news/article/1140776

post_text:
The QV boys soccer team defeated Shady Side Academy on Saturday, 2-0.

QV advances to the WPIAL 2A Championships and will face Deer Lakes this Friday, 11/1, at 8 PM at Highmark Stadium. Good Luck, Quaker Valley!

Tickets Prices:

Students $5; Adults $10

Tickets may be purchased at the Highmark Stadium ticket window on the West Side of the stadium or through ticketmaster.com.

The paid admission entitles the spectator to watch all games that day. There is no pre-sale of tickets. Pre-Kindergarten children will be admitted free when accompanied by an adult. There is a no re-entry policy for all soccer games at Highmark Stadium.

post_text: Mr. Rea braved the chilly temps this morning to reward students for their efforts in the annual Race for Education at Osborne Elementary. Thank you to our HSA, parents, students, teachers, community members, and race sponsors for another successful Race for Education. We raised over $28,000 to support our students and teachers.

post_text: Kindergarten students at Osborne Elementary School hosted a tea party with their favorite bears Friday afternoon. Students rotated to different stations around each kindergarten classroom that focused on math, writing, and science skills. The children also were encouraged to dress 'fancy' for the day and visit each center with their bear.
